<DOC><DOCNO> AP880318-0043 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0615EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     03-18 0803</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,780</SECOND><HEAD>Dole A Winner With Student Leaders</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sen. Bob Dole, who has taken a beating at thehands of George Bush in nearly all the Republican presidentialprimaries, won hands down among a select group of young voters.   One hundred and two high school student leaders were asked inJanuary to name their favorite candidates in both the Republicanand Democratic parties. The students are winners of the Century IIILeaders scholarship program sponsored by the National Associationof Secondary School Principals and Shell Oil Co.   On the GOP side, the student leaders chose Dole over Bush by 70percent to 15 percent, with 10 percent naming Pete du Pont, who isnow out of the race, according to survey results released Thursday.   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was the favorite on theDemocratic side, getting 37 percent of the students' votes to 17percent for Sens. Albert Gore Jr. and Paul Simon, 10 percent forBruce Babbitt (now a dropout), 9 percent for Rep. Richard Gephardtand just 4 percent for Jesse Jackson.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Arab League Envoy Gives Robertson ``Kiss of Death'' Endorsement</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Arab League's envoy to the United Statesgave what he called ``the kiss of death'' to Pat Robertson'spresidential bid _ an endorsement.   After a speech Thursday in which he denounced Israel, lauded thePalestine Liberation Organization and blasted Congress and theReagan administration, ambassador Clovis Maksoud was invited tostate his preference in the presidential sweepstakes.   ``Well, I don't want to say who's the preferred presidentialcandidate, because that almost would be the kiss of death, so Iwould suggest _ I would suggest Pat Robertson,'' Maksoud said,provoking laughter from the audience.   Robertson is an outspoken supporter of Israel.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>N.J. Leader Drops Plan To Send Uncommitted Slate To DemocraticConvention</HEAD><TEXT>   TRENTON, N.J. (AM) _ New Jersey Senate Democratic Leader JohnLynch says he will abandon a proposal to send a slate ofuncommitted delegates to the Democratic National Convention.   Lynch said Thursday he will drop a movement he headed and bow tothe request of Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.   Bradley met with Democratic leaders Wednesday and asked them todrop their efforts toward an uncommitted slate, saying the drivecould be interpreted outside the state as a movement to back him asa presidential candidate.   ``Senator Bradley feels the uncommitted movement would beperceived as a `stalking horse' for a candidacy at a brokeredconvention,'' Lynch said.   Lynch has said an uncommitted slate could enable New Jersey toplay a decisive role at the convention if no Democratic candidatewins a majority of delegates in the primaries.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Dole Fan Urges Senator To Drop Out Of Race</HEAD><DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Robert Dole's staunchest New Jerseysupporter, Assembly GOP Leader Chuck Haytaian, says the Kansassenator should drop out of the race for the Republican presidentialnomination.   Haytaian, who is chairman of Dole's New Jersey campaign, saidThursday that Vice President George Bush has the nomination all butlocked up, and Dole ought to face reality.   ``He knows how to count numbers,'' said Haytaian. ``If he looksat the delegate numbers for Bush, the numbers should tell him whatto do.''   Haytaian added he would continue to support Dole as long as heremains a candidate.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Jackson Campaign May Seek Postponement Of S.C. County Conventions</HEAD><DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The coordinator of Jesse Jackson'spresidential campaign in South Carolina says he may ask a judge topostpone Monday's county conventions.   Kevin Gray said Thursday he is frustrated by the inefficiency ofthe Democratic caucus and the absence of delegate lists.   ``The caucus process is rearing its ugly head,'' said Gray, oneof a growing number of Democrats who believe the party should beholding a primary.   Eighteen counties' conventions are meeting Monday and the other28 counties are meeting March 28. Jackson was the overwhelmingwinner at Saturday's 1,788 precinct caucus meetings.   Gray said it's important to all of the campaigns to have accessto the delegate lists so they can make sure their delegates knowwhere and when to go to the county conventions and so they can seekthe support of uncommitted delegates.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>LaRouche Ruled Off Indiana Ballot</HEAD><DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche has beenruled off Indiana's Democratic presidential primary ballot becauseof inadequate petition signatures.   The State Election Board concluded on Thursday that LaRouche'ssupporters had failed to meet the requirements for signatures toqualify him for the May 3 ballot.   Indiana law requires 500 signatures from each of the state's 10congressional districts. The LaRouche petitions met thatrequirement in nine districts and had more than 5,000 signaturesoverall, but the petitions had only 325 signatures in the 10thDistrict, according to election board Chairman John R. Whitaker.</TEXT></DOC>